text: Isolation of an anthrabenzoxocinone 1.264-C from Streptomyces sp. FXJ1.264 and absolute conﬁguration determination of the anthrabenzoxocinones Haiyan Chen a,b, Ning Liu a, Ying Huang a,⇑ Article history: Received 9 October 2013 Accepted 14 November 2013 Anthrabenzoxocinones (ABXs) are hexacyclic aromatic com- pounds that are isolated from different actinomycetes. The ﬁrst ABX compound BE-24566B 1 was obtained from Streptomyces violaceusniger A24566 (Fig. 1). BE-24566B possesses antibacterial activity against Gram-positive bacteria including methicillin-resis- tant Staphylococcus aureus.1 L-755805 2, from the actinomycete strain MA7150, was proposed to have an identical planar structure as BE-24566B and was reported as an endothelin binding inhibi- tor.2 ((cid:2))-ABX 3 is an enantiomer of BE-24566B. Compound 3 and its analogue ((cid:2))-bischloroanthrabenzoxocinone 4 [((cid:2))-BABX] were found to be liver X receptor antagonists from Streptomyces sp. MA6657 (Fig. 1). They also exhibit comparable antibiotic activity against Gram-positive bacteria to BE-24566B.3 Two stereogenic centers (C6 and C16) exist in the ABX molecules. To date, none of the ABXs have had their absolute conﬁguration determined, which is important for structure–activity relationship investigations and biosynthetic studies. 0957-4166/$ - see front matter (cid:2) 2013 Elsevier Ltd. Chen). j o u r n a l h o m e p a g e : w w w . e l s e v i e r . c o m / l o c a t e / t e t a s y The anthrabenzoxocinones (ABXs) are hexacyclic aromatic compounds with various bioactivities. Some ABXs with two stereogenic carbon centers have been isolated from different actinomycetes. However, none of them have an absolute conﬁguration assigned, which precludes further studies on the struc- ture–activity relationship and biosynthetic mechanisms of the ABXs. An ABX compound 1.264-C was iso- lated from Streptomyces sp. FXJ1.264. The absolute conﬁguration of 1.264-C was characterized by X-ray crystallographic, electronic, and experimental circular dichroism (CD) analyses. Based on the reported CD and speciﬁc rotation data, the absolute conﬁgurations of several other ABXs were also assigned. During our studies to explore natural product resources from microorganisms in special habitats, ABX compound 1.264-C 5 was uncovered from Streptomyces sp. FXJ1.264. The strain was isolated from acidic laterite and was reported previously as a producer of polyether compounds etheromycin (1.264-A) and 1.264-B.4 Herein we report the isolation and structural elucidation of 1.264-C. The absolute conﬁguration of 1.264-C was solved through X-ray crystallographic and circular dichroism (CD) analy- ses. Based on the CD and optical rotation data from the literature, the absolute conﬁgurations of several other ABXs [BE-24566B, ((cid:2))-ABX and BABX] were also proposed. When cultured in a solid GYM medium, S. sp. FXJ1.264 pro- duced a yellow substance in large amounts. Approximately 2. 50 mg of the substance, known as 1.264-C, was puriﬁed from 5 L of culture. High resolution electrospray ionization-mass spectrome- try (HRESI-MS) of 1.264-C indicated a molecular formula of C27H24O7 with [M+H]+ ion at m/z 461.1597 (461.1595 calculated for the [M+H]+ ion). A database search in chemical banks (e.g., DNP2013) revealed that it had the same molecular formula as ABX compounds BE-24566B, L-755805, and ((cid:2))-ABX. Subsequent UV, 1H, and 13C NMR analyses indicated that 1.264-C should have the same planar structure as the three aforementioned ABXs. A comparison of the NMR data of 1.264-C and BE-24566B in a d6-acetone solution at room temperature is shown in Table 1. In order to solve the spatial conﬁguration of the ABXs, 1.264-C was tested under various conditions for crystallization. Pale yellow prism crystals of 1.264-C were obtained with the vapor diffusion method in acetonitrile. The X-ray crystallographic analysis was performed with a Bruker P4 diffractometer equipped with graphite monochromatized Mo Ka radiation (k = 0.71073 Å) at 295 K. The relative conﬁguration of 1.264-C was narrowed down to be either (6S,16S) or (6R,16R) (Fig. 2). The (6R,16R)-enantio- mer should have a mirror symmetric spectrum. CD analysis of 1.264-C resulted in a spectrum matched with the former enantio- mer, indicating that the absolute conﬁguration of 1.264-C is (6S,16S) (Fig. 3, Table 2). Previous analysis showed that BE-24566B has a very similar CD spectrum to 1.264-C, indicating that its absolute conﬁguration is also (6S,16S) (Table 2). The enantiomer of BE-24566B, ((cid:2))-ABX was proposed to be (6R,16R) according to its CD data. ((cid:2))-BABX should also be (6R,16R) since it has a very similar CD spectrum to that of ((cid:2))-ABX (Table 2). The absolute conﬁgurations of those ABXs are shown in Figure 4. The DFT (density functional theory) calculated speciﬁc rotation data of all of the ABXs also support the assignments (Table 2). Based on the results of 1.264-C and the reported CD and speciﬁc rotation data of other ABXs, the absolute conﬁgu- rations of BE-24566B, ((cid:2))-ABX, and ((cid:2))-BABX were determined, which sets the stage for further structure–activity relationship studies of the ABXs and should help determine the biosynthetic pathway.

Melting point was measured on an X-4 micro-melting point apparatus (Yuhua Co. Ltd, Henan, China). HRESI-MS was performed on an Agilent 1260 HPLC/6520 QTOF-MS instrument (Santa Clara, CA).1H and 13C NMR spectra were recorded at room temperature on a Bruker-500 NMR spectrometer (Billerica, MA). Optical rota- tions were measured on the Anton Paar MCP-200 digital automatic polarimeter (Graz, Austria) with solvent dichloromethane. CD spectra were measured on Chirascan Circular Dichroism Spectrom- eter (Surrey, UK) with solvent MeOH. X-ray crystallographic data were collected with a Bruker P4 diffractometer (Billerica, MA). S. sp. FXJ1.264 was grown on GYM plates (glucose 4.0 g, yeast extract 4.0 g, malt extract 10.0 g, CaCO3 2.0 g, soluble starch 20.0 g, agar 15.0 g, distilled water 1.0 L, adjust to pH 7.2) for spore collection. The S. sp. FXJ1.264 spores were inoculated directly onto a solid GYM medium for 1.264-C production.4 After being cultured at 28 (cid:3)C for 12 days, the total 5 L medium was chopped and extracted three times with ethanol. Following solvent removal in vacuo, the sample was subjected to a silica gel chromatography (100–200 mesh, Qingdao Haiyang chemical) eluted with gradient chloroform-acetone (from 100:0 to 50:50). Upon recrystallization from acetonitrile by using the vapor dif- fusion method, pale yellow crystals of 1.264-C were obtained. A crystal (0.2 (cid:4) 0.2 (cid:4) 0.5 mm) was separated from the sample and mounted on a glass ﬁber, and data were recorded on a Bruker P4 diffractometer equipped with graphite monochromatized Mo Ka radiation (k = 0.71073 Å) at 295 K. Crystallographic data have been deposited in the Cambridge Crystallographic Data Center with the deposition number CCDC 964390.5 A systematic conformational search of 1.264-C and ((cid:2))- (6R,16R)-BABX was carried out by the Conﬂex 7.0 program.6 The 1.264-C indicated a stable conformation for the rigid hexacyclic aromatic structure while BABX gave two stable conformations for the 3-OMe free rotation (BABX1 and BABX2). All of the stable con- formations were further optimized by the B3LYP function and the 6-311G⁄⁄ basis set. The B3LYP/6-311G⁄⁄ harmonic vibrational fre- quencies were further calculated to conﬁrm their stability. The ECD of 1.264-C was calculated using the TD-DFT (Time-dependent density functional theory) method at the PBE0/6-311++G⁄⁄ level.7 The speciﬁc rotations of 1.264-C and ((cid:2))-BABX were calculated at the B3LYP/6-311G⁄⁄ level.
